  "prompt": "To which class cin and cout belongs?",
  "response": "In C++, `cin` and `cout` are objects that belong to the `std` (standard) namespace and are instances of classes defined in the `<iostream>` library.\n\n- **`cin`** is an object of the `std::cin` class, which is an instance of the `std::istream` class. It is used for standard input (e.g., reading from the keyboard).\n  \n- **`cout`** is an object of the `std::cout` class, which is an instance of the `std::ostream` class. It is used for standard output (e.g., writing to the console).\n\nHere\u2019s a brief summary:\n- `cin` \u2192 `std::istream`\n- `cout` \u2192 `std::ostream`\n\nThese objects are part of the Standard Template Library (STL) in C++. When using them, you typically include the `<iostream>` header and use the `std` namespace (either explicitly or with a `using namespace std;` directive). For example:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n    int num;\n    cout << \"Enter a number: \";  // Output using cout\n    cin >> num;                  // Input using cin\n    cout << \"You entered: \" << num << endl;\n    return 0;\n}\n```",
